result.execSummary:
The defendant Cody J. Bunkelman was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Resisting or Obstructing an Officer [Modifiers: Repeater], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).
  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Repeater, Domestic Abuse Assessments, Domestic Abuse], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

If revoked the defendant has 60 days credit for time served.  Defendant ordered to report to Probation and Parole the next morning (06/09/2022).
Concurrent with: Probation is concurrent on Ct 4 and Ct 5 in this same case, as are the conditions thereof unless otherwise specified.   Probation is also concurrent in cases 22CF12, 21CF116, and 21CF137

miscConds.notes: The defendant is to submit to an Alcohol and Other Drug Assessment (AODA) and follow the recommendations, releasing the findings to the agent.

Defendant to maintain absolute sobriety.  The defendant shall have no contact with T.R. of any kind, whether direct or indirect, including in person, in writing, by phone, by e-mail or other electronic means, through a third party or in any other way.  After 2 years and if defendant has completed domestic violence  programming, AODA and has maintained absolute sobriety and with the Agent's and TR's approval, the no contact may be lifted.   Defendant was warned by the Court about the seriousness of following the no contact condition as stated in WI Stat. 973.049 and 941.39
The defendant shall pay Department of Correction fees as directed by the agent.

Defendant shall attend counseling, treatments, programming, evaluations as deemed appropriate by the agent releasing all records to the agent upon request   Defendant shall undergo a Domestic Violence Assessment and follow through with any recommendations.

Fees and costs to be paid out of bond.  Defendant is ordered to pay the DNA surcharge, and to make arrangements to provide a DNA sample, within 48 hours, for testing through the Clark County Sheriff Department or if on probation, to the Department of Corrections as is required in all criminal convictions.
